==English==
===Etymology===
From Late Anglo-Saxon [[flanc]], from Old French [[flanc]], from a Germanic source, probably Frankish ''*hlanca''

===Pronunciation===
* [[Wiktionary:Pronunciation_key|IPA]]: /flæŋk/

===Noun===
'''flank''' (plural '''[[flanks]]''')
# The flesh between the last rib and the hip; the side
# A cut of meat from the flank of an animal
# The side of a military formation
# A side of something

====Synonyms====
(''all'')
* [[side]]

(''side of formation'')
* [[wing]]

===Verb===
'''to flank''' ('''[[flanks]]''', '''[[flanking]]''', '''[[flanked]]''') ''transitive''
# To attack the flank(s) of something
# To defend the flank(s) of something
# To place to the side(s) of something
# To be placed to the side(s) of something (usually in terms of two objects, one on each side)